<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-158-550  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 158 550.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Feb 22 1989 n1449 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A century after its discovery the soliton is making waves.andO;(high-speed optical communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many scientists believe that the soliton holds the key to thehigh-speed transmission and computing techniques of the next 100years.andP;  The soliton is a pulse or wave that retains its shape asit moves through a particular medium.andP;  It was first discovered inthe late nineteenth century by a Scottish engineer who watchedwaves going down an industrial canal.andP;  The soliton is now beingstudied within the glass channels of optical fibers that are notover ten-millionths of a meter wide.andP;  In 1988 scientists at BellLaboratories sent soliton light pulses 2,480 miles around a fiberloop without any electrical regeneration.andP;  The pulse was pumped bya laser as it traveled within the fiber loop.andP;  The soliton may yethave its day but optical data transmission and optical computersare still in the research lab.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical ComputersFuture TechnologiesResearch and DevelopmentFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraphcartoon.andO;Caption:   (Schematic of the fibre loop mirror). (chart)(Results of the periodic behavior of the self-switching solitons).andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>